<% provide(:title, 'Regex Matches Timeout Demo') %>
<h1>Regex Matches Timeout Demo <small><%= link_to "JSON", debugger_test_regex_timeout_path(format: :json) %></small></h1>

<p class="lead">
  Tests the per-match timeout added to the Dynamic Instrumentation expression
  language <code>matches</code> operator in dd-trace-rb PR
  <a href="https://github.com/DataDog/dd-trace-rb/pull/5908">#5908</a>.
  Each <code>matches</code> evaluation is bounded to 500ms
  (<code>Evaluator::MATCHES_TIMEOUT_SECONDS</code>).
</p>

<div class="panel panel-info">
  <div class="panel-heading"><h4 class="panel-title">How to Test</h4></div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <ol>
      <li>
        In Datadog, set a <strong>method probe</strong> on
        <code><%= @target[:class_name] %>#<%= @target[:method_name] %></code>
        with the condition below.
      </li>
      <li>
        Condition (DSL):
        <pre>matches(haystack, "<%= @pattern %>")</pre>
        Condition (JSON AST):
        <pre>{"matches": [{"ref": "haystack"}, "<%= @pattern %>"]}</pre>
      </li>
      <li>Wait for the probe to appear as active on <%= link_to "DI Status", di_status_path %>.</li>
      <li>
        Click <strong>Run</strong> below. It calls the method once per input.
        DI evaluates the condition on each call, running the regexp against the
        haystack.
      </li>
      <li>
        Observe the per-input timing. The pathological input causes catastrophic
        backtracking: with PR #5908 its evaluation is bounded to ~500ms; without
        the fix the request hangs.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="panel panel-default">
  <div class="panel-heading"><h4 class="panel-title">Probe Target</h4></div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <dl class="dl-horizontal">
      <dt>Class:</dt><dd><code><%= @target[:class_name] %></code></dd>
      <dt>Method:</dt><dd><code><%= @target[:method_name] %></code></dd>
      <dt>File:</dt><dd><code><%= @target[:file] %></code></dd>
      <dt>Line:</dt><dd><%= @target[:line] %></dd>
    </dl>

    <table class="table table-condensed table-bordered">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Input</th><th>Bytes</th><th>Haystack</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <% @inputs.each do |input| %>
          <tr>
            <td><%= input[:label] %></td>
            <td><%= input[:haystack].bytesize %></td>
            <td><code><%= input[:haystack] %></code></td>
          </tr>
        <% end %>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="well">
  <h4>Run the Demo</h4>
  <p class="text-muted" style="margin-bottom: 15px;">
    Calls <code><%= @target[:class_name] %>#<%= @target[:method_name] %></code>
    once per input above. Timing reflects DI condition evaluation only while a
    probe is active. Without PR #5908 the pathological input will hang this
    request.
  </p>
  <a href="<%= debugger_test_regex_timeout_run_path %>" class="di-demo-btn">
    <strong>Run</strong><br>
    <small>Call the method with every input</small>
  </a>

  <pre id="di-demo-result" style="margin-top: 15px;">Click Run to trigger the demo.</pre>
</div>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll('.di-demo-btn').forEach(function(btn) {
    btn.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      var url = this.getAttribute('href');
      var resultEl = document.getElementById('di-demo-result');

      resultEl.textContent = 'Running...';

      fetch(url)
        .then(function(res) {
          return res.text().then(function(text) {
            if (!res.ok) {
              throw new Error('HTTP ' + res.status + ': ' + text.substring(0, 200));
            }
            return text;
          });
        })
        .then(function(text) {
          resultEl.textContent = text;
        })
        .catch(function(err) {
          resultEl.textContent = 'Error: ' + err;
        });
    });
  });
</script>

<div class="panel panel-default">
  <div class="panel-heading"><h4 class="panel-title">Background</h4></div>
  <div class="panel-body">
    <p>
      Regular expressions in DI probe conditions and capture expressions are
      customer input. A catastrophic-backtracking pattern such as
      <code><%= @pattern %></code> can take unbounded time on a crafted input,
      so DI must cap each match. PR #5908 bounds every <code>matches</code>
      evaluation to <code>Evaluator::MATCHES_TIMEOUT_SECONDS</code> (500ms).
    </p>
    <p>
      The timeout mechanism differs by Ruby version. On Ruby 3.2+ the bound is
      baked into the compiled <code>Regexp</code> via the in-engine
      <code>timeout:</code> keyword. On Ruby &lt; 3.2 (this app runs
      <code><%= RUBY_VERSION %></code>) the bound is applied with
      <code>Timeout.timeout</code> around the match.
    </p>
    <p>
      When the bound is hit, DI catches the timeout during condition evaluation
      and treats the condition as unsatisfied. The instrumented method returns
      normally, so this page works whether or not a probe is set.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
